The Republican Party's strategy against Obama's reelection
Republican leaders have justified their policies on the necessity of fighting electoral fraud.
But the Brennan Center calls such fraud a myth, saying that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die after being struck by lightning.
Republican lawyers have only documented 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in the last decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States has statewide responsibility for organizing federal elections.
And in that spirit, most U.S. governments have been enacting new laws since 2009 that make it harder to vote or register to vote.
This phenomenon has seen a surge since the November 2010 elections, during which 675 new Republican representatives were added in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills restricting voting rights were introduced in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to present photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for early elections, invalidate the right to register on the day of the elections and deprive citizens with criminal records of the right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of the Indiana law was upheld in 2008 by the U.S. Supreme Court.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend this procedure to other states.
In the past two years, 34 states have passed such laws to force voters to produce photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by their state government.
Furthermore, about five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
Additionally, the required ID often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affecting mainly young people, minorities and low-income people.
25% of African Americans, 15% of those with incomes under $35,000, 18% of those over 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their sympathy for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their school's photo ID in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who vote for Republican candidates to use the cards issued by those clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for elections.
The first such requirement was put in place by Arizona.
Since 2011, about a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported laws in eight states that would abolish voter registration on Election Day.
They also restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register some 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% decrease in the number of new voters registered in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at shortening the early election period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, African-Americans made up 33% of the early voters, even though African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
The same thing happened with the Spanish.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who made up 76% of all voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted early.
Of course, the Democratic legislators and their supporters have been very vocal in opposing the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Democratic governors have blocked several bills with their vetoes.
In an effort to suspend the most controversial laws, the U.S. Attorney General even intervened.
They've managed to contain some of the damage.
For example, laws requiring photo IDs have been adopted by only 16 of 34 states.
However, the new rules will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Critics of democracy mostly speak of the bias of the passed laws, which they see as an obvious attempt to influence the outcome of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain today: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
