The Higgs boson studied
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson sparked a justifiable stir last summer.
There's a theory that this boson is involved in the mechanism that's responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And then there's the last particle that's predicted by the Standard Model -- our best or "least bad" explanation for the nature and behavior of matter -- that hasn't been observed empirically yet.
But physicists are still not 100% sure that it is the Higgs boson.
He doesn't doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson as predicted by the Standard Model.
New data released this week during the big physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm it, but we still don't have all the data to be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume that it's the Higgs boson, because the risk of error seems to be small, and let's look at what's really going on.
There is a law in this world that is absolutely unquestionable, that no two things can occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard or you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It further divides particle physics into two categories.
On the one hand, we find the orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow Pauli's principle.
And at the other end of the spectrum are bosons, mean anarchists who don't value anything at all -- certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups by the device (which is absolutely amazing, by the way) called The Particle Adventure, at Berkeley Labs: mesons, which we'll leave unnoticed here, and "force particles", which spread great forces of nature and with which the Higgs boson is probably related in some way.
But it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic as one might think.
If you are reading this article, it is because of an unusually common boson: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of the electromagnetic force.
When charged particles accelerate or change direction, they "disrupt" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - one of the bosons, "carriers of force".
More stable field
So it's the same with the Higgs boson, except that to "disturb" it takes another field, the Higgs field, for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it needs to reach very high energy levels to be excited, much like the frozen surface of a pond, which only a very large bowl will erode.
So it's necessary to use a particle accelerator as big as the one at CERN - a large hadron accelerator with a 27 km radius of tangent rings! - to develop this energy.
The electromagnetic field analogy is useful again to explain the relationship between the Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or materials react to an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do that, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never stand alone on a refrigerator.
And it's also true that not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have some mass, while the others (like the photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what is all this research, what does it "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, this is a validation of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
And there are not a lot of physicists who literally wish they could find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space for "new physics" and fill in some of the gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model is still very flawed, providing no explanation for gravity (wow!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's mass (wow again!).
But until now, CERN has not found such contradictions.
The answer
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr and Mrs Novákov is very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to think that there will be none.
Look, back in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would bring.
They were expecting scientific applications, but nothing more.
The physicist Willard Boyle -- who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam -- the previous beams were pulsed -- in 1962, I've said it before -- the laser was initially thought of as a sort of "laboratory toy".
Just imagine that.
And, moreover, the application can also stem from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle invented a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle didn't originally plan it that way, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world, and it won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, that doesn't mean that the activities around the LHC have to change our lives, but it does mean that you never really know...
