The key step is to record this new transaction in this ledger.
It's done by solving a mathematical problem given to the computers, and the solver, some kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to fill in this extra line.
This is the phase of file cutting; that is, transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital print.
The computers "take" this new transaction and add a number to it, only to "cut" the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a specific print (a lot of zero at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then indelibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If a user wants to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (up to ten minutes) for fraudulent purposes, the network will only confirm one of the two transactions - the other will be omitted because each has a different footprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is divided regularly in two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but it can be divided by 100 millionths, so there's room for margin here...
The difficulty of the task also increases with increasing computational levels.
The network has had its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The gap in usage is not related to the protocol itself", assures Pierre Noizat, founder of Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also monitors the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But the same problem applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia are rejecting gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, are embracing them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the ledger of current accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the "giant discounts" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul to convert bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who also authored a textbook on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (with real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions, which makes them cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easily configurable at dealerships where no new terminals or software need to be installed.
Just give the address, which can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who claims he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement towards challenging hierarchical systems and towards more horizontal systems.
"It's going to be a while before Bitcoin takes hold, but 2013 could be the deciding year", he predicts.
In addition, the ECB's report envisages a reassessment of the various risks which are currently considered to be heightened if this type of money is to succeed.
