The difficult work of the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided country in history, with a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has chosen to play the role of a pawn.
On Wednesday, he announced that, despite everyone else's opinion, the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the day after tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave the assembly two more months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been amended many times, which undermines the country's constitutional stability and leads to legal disputes.
This new initiative only reinforced the country's division.
From the opposition's point of view, the president continues in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "break his word" and "trample on the law".
But its supporters assure that it is a means to quickly turn around the constitutional and political crisis and speed up the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
It's a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to back down from its intention to explain the text to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it's also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the country is roiled by protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American magazine Time, Muhammad Morsi seems confident that the Egyptians will vote for him.
Especially since this hastily organised vote is putting the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: "Either you approve my text or I will keep my unlimited powers", which would otherwise end with the adoption of the new constitution.
And in this particular atmosphere, yesterday, 85 members of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most of the liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitution was proclaimed, they knocked on the door saying they had no chance to enforce their views.
Human rights activists, civil society, and members of religious minorities have emulated their steps.
To achieve tolerability, 11 of the replacement ranks were rushed in yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, articles of the constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further pondered that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... the prayer hour, when some committee members felt that the hours in the meeting room were not properly arranged.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the key requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for the rest of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", object liberals, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
They say the Islamization of the constitution is done through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers on al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular on the question of the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "those who are called upon to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This can be seen as the beginning of theocracy".
The concerns of liberals are further fuelled by the fact that the next university president should be less moderate than the current one.
"There has been no concrete religious impact so far.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of them graduated from French schools", says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that "there may be some contradictions in the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used therein are part of the religious vocabulary.
There is a particular reference to "fiqh".
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this".
The text approved yesterday is highly criticized, apart from the religious aspects, because of the expanded powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant reduction in their numbers compared to the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the army, the audit of the defence budget will not be carried out by parliament but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, the civil trial will not be prohibited in military courts, as the Human Rights Association has demanded.
The association expresses its doubts about the text, which it considers to be anti-freedom.
The criminal offence of blasphemy is maintained and insulting is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, none of the articles address women's protection, points out Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
She says the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to give a televised address last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then demonstrate on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the belly button of the world and the sea of saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comforts, and the untouched nature.
AaF has identified the top five reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping Sacred Places
To visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God's mercy will descend upon all who enter this "bath".
And Galilee - the site of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm, and filling nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples and after his resurrection.
But the most sacred places are in Jerusalem.
Here believers walk the Way of Sorrows, or Jesus' Way of the Cross (Via Dolorosa in Latin).
It begins at the Fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial was held, passes through the streets of the Old City and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - the place of the crucifixion, the anointing stone, and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is a symbolic Christian world umbilicus, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem was built on the spot where, according to Christian legend, the tree grew from which they made the cross for Jesus' crucifixion.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of various faiths leave notes with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take the road vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remain from a secret refuge from the enemy that Herod the Great built in 25 B.C. for his family.
The wreckage is located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are involved in mountaineering can reach it on their own.
The rest will take the cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1,600 to 2,040 meters, is the famous Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists during the winter months.
A shuttle bus takes tourists from the foot of the hill to this ski paradise.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, the mountain was said to be the home of pagan gods.
Visiting a unique museum
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in caves in the Judean desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
The exhibition is widely represented by the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Baths Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figures of bath users and bath nurses of the time.
In Caesarea, the unique private Ralli Museum is worth a visit, where you can admire the sculptures of Dalí and Rodén.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and gifts are strictly rejected.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum, or Yad Vashem, in Tel Aviv - tells the story of one of the most dramatic aspects of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go in, and you're in complete darkness.
The stars are shining.
And they say the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improving Your Health
Israel's three main spa centers are spread along the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is a good place to swim in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees Celsius and the air is heated to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea is, by the way, the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest point on the planet - 417 meters below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that is easy to keep afloat even for people who cannot swim.
The scenery is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to get a treatment using salt water, brine, and medicinal mud, which can treat medical problems like dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal your damaged nerves.
Touch the mysterious past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the small town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city are found in the earliest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Indeed, tourists love to wander through narrow lanes named after the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the alley of "your" sign, luck will be favorable.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come from all over Israel and even from other countries to have their picture taken.
And in Caesarea, King Herod's city, you can walk through the Roman theater and "capture" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
It is better to take along money, not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
The city's main means of transport are buses, but Jerusalem is served by a high-speed tram, and Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
It's basically a subway cable car.
Traveling by all forms of public transport costs 6 shekels, which means you can drive 1.5 hours with a transfer.
In Israel, the Sabbath is observed according to Jewish tradition.
From Friday evening until sundown on Saturday, markets, shops, and public transportation are closed.
And Sunday morning is the start of the work week.
In many cafes, restaurants, and hotels, you will only get kosher food: with the exception of pork, seafood, shellfish, and foods containing a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a wide selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, a variety of sauces, ground chickpeas - falafel, fruit, and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
There are, however, many well-fed kittens that gracefully "wander about according to their tastes".
In the evening, you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The leading cats love crowded places and indulge in every kind of goodness with gusto.
Car rental will cost from $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the make of the car.
Plus insurance, $15 a day.
And borrowing a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets are on average 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
The largest number of visitors came from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, and Ukraine.
The number of Ukrainian tourists visiting the Promised Land from January to October 2012 was 118,8 thousand, 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the visa waiver of 9 February 2011.
"Great and powerful" announces to Moscow: emigrants will save money on language
While MPs and human rights activists are still debating the compulsory language test law, scammers have already appeared in the country selling "fake" certificates
Each year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support their families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force that requires every migrant worker to pass a Russian language test.
For the time being, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the service, housing and communal, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that in time, the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the tests will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the fundamentals of law.
Proof of language proficiency will also be required for obtaining and renewing a work permit.
The exception applies only to nationals of countries where Russian is an official language.
People who successfully achieved certification and an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also not subject to this law.
Use, conviction and protection of rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the exam in any city; more than 160 such centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to promote the introduction of testing was also supported by the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights activists were able to ask the question in the press many times: What will it really bring?
What changes the obligation to know the language for Russians and for visitors themselves?
First of all, the immigration officials answer, it will reduce the number of people who suffer as a result of "slave labor".
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of FMS Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights should be initiated before their departure.
Only the system of organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise with unskilled, uneducated, unlanguageable and unmedicated immigrants.
Without knowledge of the language, the prospective migrant is doomed to clash with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "pass" to the horrible, cramped hostels where he and dozens of others like him will languish for months without food and documents and toil for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We've been getting a lot of complaints from our migrant workers.
"They are promised one thing in their country, but when they arrive they are cheated, their passports are confiscated, they are not paid the wages they were promised", confirms the head of the Tajik Central Administration for Labour Migration, Ms. Tolib Sharipov.
Don't you dare!
Not least because many Central Asian citizens who intend to go to Russia to work admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they are going to but also have no experience in the job.
Of course, it is not so much their fault as their misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least an adequate basic education.
Their families also need to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, groomed, and equipped for school.
As children reach productive age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without the language, it's hard, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
True, with regard to the language test law, human rights defenders point to one important point.
Testing will only be done on those migrants who have legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't be able to take the exam or get any other official job.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers are still living in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or unauthorized entry is prohibited".
Many of the newly arrived workers say that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all the language difficulties.
Legalisation also costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officials know we have essentially false documents, no registration, and that's what blackmail is.
"They ask for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea", Tajik citizen Umed Khushkadamov told reporters about his experience.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy yourself a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that it was not only migrants' registration documents that were falsified.
FMS employees have already confiscated several fake language test pass certificates.
The forged documents are printed on a normal colour printing press.
Of course, they did not come to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to ease the test, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is two and a half times more than passing the official test: it will cost migrant workers 3,000 rubles.
The main task in the near future is to secure the system against corruption so that workers cannot simply buy documents, according to government officials and human rights defenders.
In the meantime, the government may promise foreign workers who fail the tests the first time the time needed to complete a basic course in Russian.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
