Head of the NCC: Control of the corruption system failed because of politicians
The Czech Republic has good controls and good legislation on public procurement, but it is lagging behind in its application.
In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, the vice president of the Supreme Audit Office, Miloslav Kala, said this.
"The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - that's what I think we're missing", Kala comments on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also drawn from the joint audit of the Czech and German auditors.
As an example of misconduct, he cites Peter Neczas' approach to the so-called "swart system".
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS will not bother businessmen with its controls - is it prohibited or allowed?
"After all, the law has to be set up, and if it prohibits something, then even the prime minister cannot prevent the office from doing its job of checking and enforcing", Kala observes.
At the audit committee meeting in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties, in which the public procurement legislation in both countries was compared.
What was the point?
It's a parallel control that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how public procurement is handled, followed by national legislation and then by practice itself.
We have put all this together, and although the control is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences - in general terms, the legislation may be "harder and more perfect" here, but the practice itself is better in some parameters in Germany.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but that the application of the law itself is needed.
What does this project actually do for you, what does it do for you?
It is this kind of joint control that could help to stop the effort to clarify the laws, to reduce and improve the limits, when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economy means to get the right thing for a reasonable (but not always lowest) price, so as to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behaviour.
But by lowering the order limit, we may not necessarily achieve that.
Maybe the system will be so overwhelmed with paper that those who want to look for holes in the system will find it much easier to draw from it than if the limit were higher.
You are talking about the domestic problems with the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is this office similar to our NCO, or is it set up differently?
As for the authorities, like the NCA, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there, which is organized in the same way as us, also has a college, only it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities proceed in a similar way.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but because Germany is a federal state, the accounting courts are also at the level of the individual federal states - a system which differs somewhat from ours.
The BRH can only control federal money, which in our country is state resources.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the Federal Accounting Courts.
As for the legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to compare this without specific data, but in some respects Germany is often cited as a model, but it is not certain that it is better in all respects.
So does it have to be because they have better controllers?
I'm sure you don't, but I'm telling you again, I don't like comparisons like that.
But it should be said that even the countries we consider to be role models face a whole host of challenges.
Otherwise, there's no point in working with our office, is there?
As regards the national legislation, what has been the effect of the amendment of the Public Procurement Act for your office?
Since the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in the control measures.
Since we do ex post checks, there's a certain amount of delay to be expected.
We are only seeing this in the process of preparing future checks - we have launched our new tool "detection of uneconomic risks" through which we have searched and analysed almost 14,000 public contracts - where, of course, the changes will be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of certain types of tendering procedures will be adjusted and so on.
So, do you see the passage of this bill as a benefit or as an additional burden on the bureaucracy?
I think this bill is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it's confirmed.
The problem that can arise is that the rules will become "tougher" and it will be impossible to follow them.
Under the previous rules, the controlled persons are already obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the Regional Council) to ensure that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth making the law more stringent?
I don't think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit a formal error that has no impact on decision-making.
