Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at a meeting of European Space Agency ministers, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, the second from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and has participated in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had been exploring space before World War II, but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, on December 6, 1933, in which he presented ideas from his pioneering work Introduction to Cosmonautics.
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 he won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his entry into spacecraft science in France.
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned proponent of spaceflight, and his contributions were recognized by having one of the craters on the far side of the moon named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway dredge was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the design is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It's not even clear whether the missile was intended to be used to launch the drone or to slow it down.
Information about this drill is known only from the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to use rocket-propelled grenades.
The research was carried out by the Armament Technology Unit in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolf and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
It is clear from the archival material that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, the arrival of German troops interrupted the research.
In 1937, a photoelectric fighter rocket designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work Rakieta - aerial torpedo and aerial rocket-bomber by Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were dealt with by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activities were ended by the outbreak of war.
Further works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of the company is in the November 1954 issue of Problemy, which contains four more extensive articles on astronautry.
One, by Professor M. Subotowicz, proposes the creation of a society for the study of spacecraft.
At the time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been seeking to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn of that year, the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the very successful RM meteorological rocket (Raketa Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first flight took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, with a range of 1,800 meters, was about 80 centimeters long and weighed less than 5 kilograms.
Later, improved versions of the RM-1A were built, and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 fighter rocket flight tests were started in the Bledova Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
The next development type was to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 missile was to have a range of 14.5 km and its task was to monitor high-altitude winds.
However, in 1962 further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, 510 cm long, launch weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A had a capacity of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1B had a capacity of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C had a capacity of 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aeronautics developed the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 had a launch weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in the Interkosmos program in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
