Controversial EU regulations include mandatory biofuel mixing, which is harmful to nature, a ban on reliable mercury thermometers simply because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, and a cage-size directive that has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term "butter" or the exclusion of traditional light bulbs has also faced criticism in the past.
A good banana should be fourteen centimeters long.
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of a particular business or industrial lobby, whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (the Czech Republic is now also threatening to veto the demands of its banks).
The lobby also had interests in ensuring that, for example, the highest quality bananas in the Union had to be at least 14 cm long and not have 'abnormal curvature'.
The European Commission has defended itself by claiming that it is merely harmonising the previously fragmented national standards which have made trade more difficult.
The EU has already relaxed its rules on fruit and vegetables, despite the opposition of some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
A candidate for the poll may also be last year's EU regulation, which requires inflatable balloons sold to be marked with a warning that children under 8 years of age should not inflate them without adult supervision.
