Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained from voting on the decision to accept Palestine.
According to US-European relations expert Stephen Szabo, this puts Berlin on the edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first signaled that it would vote against the proposal for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Why?
Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he'll support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
It was finally adopted by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that they are changing their foreign policy, from a policy that was, so to speak, led by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
The situation is made all the more difficult by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and united policy.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I think they're just settling into their role, but they're on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
The foreign policy they have in France or Britain.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German perspective?
It shows a willingness to take positions that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and its relations with certain areas, like Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other powers, and therefore Germany must protect its own interests.
Did economic interests influence the position on the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has a large market in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
So they have to be careful not to scare the public, but also the elites in Arab countries.
That's what matters.
I don't want to give it too much importance, but it's not exactly a one-sided relationship.
But it is still a major factor in the German thinking.
Did Germany's abstention from voting on two important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine, harm its relations with the United States?
I think there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the United States for the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a breakthrough as Libya.
I hope Germany will even gain some respect from it.
This signals that it must be regarded as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has been very clear about its veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration has a pretty good understanding of the European position behind it.
But, of course, because of the political situation there, he cannot take this position publicly.
I think the differences of opinion are really not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what's making it difficult for the Germans.
It would of course be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can't be part of the larger picture and they have to push things forward from their own position instead.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take the lead in the future and push Europe towards a European attitude.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, especially because of its relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player, or does it want to take the lead?
Or is the leadership role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a bigger role.
If we look at the European crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a bigger role, there is an anti-German sentiment.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be acceptable to all the different neighbors and opinions, and it's not easy.
The US' influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not currently filling that vacuum.
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's uncomfortable and it makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study together the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
