There's no manual on the new marijuana law in Colorado.
Nineteen-year-old Anthony Orozco, a high school student and football player from southeastern Colorado, faces criminal charges for what will soon be legal statewide - possession of several grams of marijuana and the pipe he used to smoke it.
Mr. Orozco said that one day in September, he was driving with some friends in Lamar, in the plains near the Kansas border, when he was stopped.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco was issued a subpoena for possession of drugs and drug-using equipment - misdemeanors punishable by a $100 fine each - and was given a trial date.
"They treated us like criminals", said Mr. Orozco.
But is he a criminal?
In the uncertain weeks since the Colorado vote to legalize small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the answer to hundreds of smaller drug cases depends more on the location than the law.
Hundreds of marijuana possession violations have already been dismissed here and in Washington State, which has passed similar measures.
The police department has stopped charging adults 21 and older for possession of small amounts, which will be legally allowed after the law takes effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in more conservative districts in Colorado have said they will continue with existing marijuana cases, and still charge people with possession.
Meanwhile, several cities from the Denver suburbs to the western mountains are voting to prevent the opening of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their communities.
"This thing is moving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next", said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Even the regulators in Washington state are getting their heads chopped off.
And they're looking for guidance on how to set up a system of licensing for cultivation, production, distribution and sale - all by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now recreational.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide", said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Licensing Board.
But as Mr. Smith admitted, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
"There is no real precedent by which we can follow", he said.
Washington's law, I-502, takes effect on December 6th, which also leaves a one-year gap during which the state's licensing system will not yet exist, but legal possession will.
And there are some intricate mechanical issues that need to be resolved during this time, such as how to balance the state's directive on "appropriate access" to licensed marijuana with its prohibition on the sale of cannabis within 330 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds or child care centers.
"Nowhere will it be harder to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area", said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly formed research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an e-mail to his officers informing them that the city prosecutor would no longer prosecute small-scale marijuana possession offenses against every citizen over the age of 21 and that police would stop charging people with these crimes "with immediate effect".
Chief Oates said police will enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and will continue to prosecute drug dealers and dealers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck is taking a tougher line.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges of possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many are facing additional charges.
"Our office is obliged to prosecute criminal offences that were criminal offences at the time they occurred", Mr Buck said in a statement.
The response was complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer charging adults with possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supports this decision, but he also decided not to dismiss all the ongoing detention cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes", he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the hands of the government and the legal system will never be easy.
And the mixed reactions across the state to this big state green experiment revealed a deep divide among local officials.
For district attorneys, it's a "cultural barrier", said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents marijuana defendants and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They've spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can't really accept that it's legal", he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana as if they were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are well on their way to becoming national test cases for drug legalization.
The defense and state agencies are planning new boundaries for legalized sales, while also anxiously awaiting instructions from the federal government, which still plans to declare the sale and cultivation of marijuana a federal crime.
The marijuana legalization advocates are hoping the Justice Department will give in.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana dealers and patients who use it that have attracted attention, the federal government has mostly kept medical marijuana businesses in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states in operation.
While drug agents are unlikely to bust through doors to intercept a small bag of drugs, they are likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana businesses authorized by the new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal action.
Even before Election Day, some local governments have approved moratoriums on any new marijuana businesses, although it will be another year or so before any businesses can open.
Last week, the city of Montrose in the western part of the state proposed a six-month ban, and it's likely to go into effect next week.
"We don't want to be in a situation where we license someone and then we have a big federal issue", said Bob Nicholson, a city councilman.
Our community voted against this amendment.
