Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I am a Conservative".
It is not just today's university students who are challenged for their beliefs.
I don't remember ever not dreaming of studying at Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother attended what I thought was the world's greatest seat of knowledge, a modern Greek symposium of the twelve motivating pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
And meanwhile, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of entering Worcester College, where I was going to study history, I packed my bags and got into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed I gave up because I objected to making love to students in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson bluntly stated that I left because I was forced to drink from broken cups.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was the subject of systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment, it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a senior adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You might ask why I'm bringing it up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students, right from the center, are suffering from similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students demanded the same rights protections as gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior College Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College claim that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks, and made to feel unwelcome".
They are asking for a position on the university's Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that they can express their views freely.
Their situation was not helped by the recent BBC Two documentary Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, a student political drama that portrayed conservatives as freaks and neo-Nazis.
The program featured alumnus Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who drove a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and had a stick with a silver head.
At other colleges, conservative students say that they are treated as "sacrificial lambs" because of the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told the Sunday newspaper that "left-wing influence is growing on the university campuses.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even meeting with us".
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is "unpleasant", while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in the JCR's approach to right-of-centre people.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion as well as to the well-being of the members", he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford, I was in a one-member minority.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and paralyzingly shy.
The hatred of the Conservative Party was the most bitter.
A year earlier, the university had voted to refuse the honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher because of cuts in funding for higher education.
From the atmosphere, even the Stalinists would tremble with fear.
During the first few days of the opening week, when the new students are meeting with each other and with the professors, I got a taste of the diaper that was to come.
I found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the pimping of conservative students, but they are willing to participate.
The timber-lined auditoriums were filled with the politics of mining strikes, privatization and the government's resistance to apartheid sanctions in South Africa.
My first lecture was about translating an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt", said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph".
I was getting pretty rough.
Professor Pitt, the little man with the face of pie dough, was very gallant.
"Do the Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students were giggling.
I was in tears.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you are too busy with social matters", Professor Pitt concluded.
I went back to my room, devastated.
I was sitting alone at dinner at school when I felt a gentle tap on my shoulder.
He was a sophomore named James, who introduced himself as a member of OUCA.
"I know who you are", he said kindly.
Unfortunately, that's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most of the Conservative first-timers pretend to be Labour.
Later, at the local tavern, I cowardly tried to pretend.
I insisted on disagreeing with everything that Thatcher said.
This trick has proven unsuccessful.
A first-year student in philosophy, politics and economics who went to Eton, ironically, said, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig".
You are infected.
The other students took notes with him.
I was perverted, dirty.
"How do conservatives love?" one asked.
They're beating each other, aren't they?
I felt like the homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the '60s.
Could I ever have a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I change to Labour and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years before me had been a purge of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who was based in my faculty.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He was barely there.
He hated the place for its petty and petty nature and for its inclination to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here", he told me.
I started driving from Oxford to my parents' house in London, seeking refuge with my unbiased metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his time at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world", he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in the city of dreams.
Even my Communist friends have always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes were blurred.
Try it again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience worsened.
My friend, also a Conservative, succumbed to pressure and renounced his beliefs.
The following week, during class, when another history professor declared in all seriousness that I was an "enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Although I was blushing with shame, I admitted that my "parents brainwashed" me and called them "old fools".
The relief was short-lived.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was my father.
He wrote two columns a week for Murdoch's paper at the time.
My door was locked.
I crouched inside, and after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
After they left, I packed my bags and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a grumpy weakling.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subjected to such intimidation and toxicity in an educational institution.
Even more tragic, it was Oxford, which not only produced 14 Conservative prime ministers, but which still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and free thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Fashion Design", which opened this week in London, ABC spoke with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisz and other famous customers of the Italian designer.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabella I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting a Valentin Garavani exhibition.
The designer confirmed this at the opening of the celebratory retrospective "Valentino: Master of Fashion Design", which presents more than 130 high-end fashion models created by his studio over the past 50 years.
"I love this castle", he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story in which "il signore" Garavani is the only protagonist, but which could not have been written without his esteemed clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rare and distant world of the aristocracy.
The first hall of the exhibition, which runs until March 3, is filled with private correspondence and photographs signed by the most important nobles, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Princess Maria-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino exposes these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a simple tailor from Voghera in northern Italy to the international idol of "Bohemian creams".
There's nothing wrong with liking royalty.
"At least they don't drop a cigarette into a great carpet, as some wonderful pop-music celebrities do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisz.
In the '60s and '70s, we lived in the Alps together and were good friends.
Valentino is an impressive host and entertains guests with grace and elegance.
"We were all very pleased to be invited to his cottage in Gstaad", explains "Heini" Thyssen's ex-wife and close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
"Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet he's a star".
Valeria Mazz is playing Valentino.
The charisma of the designer is not forgotten by the Argentinian model Valeria Mazz.
"It has been many years since we had a dinner with him after a show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome.
There were 20 of us, and between us were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of his apartment, the decorations, the food, the music, everything was reflected and he could feel his spirit.
It made everyone invited feel important and loved", recalls the top model who began working with him during Paris Fashion Week in 1995.
"He never goes out of style because his designs are works of art", he concludes.
A parade of nobility
Gravani's life is not a story of obsession, but of true love.
He loves people with good education and better degrees and they love him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been converted into a distinctive 70 metre long passage offering role-playing: the visitor turns into a model and walks through the passage to observe the "custom" of dreams worn by Valentine's masterpieces such as the dress chosen by Jackie Kennedy for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume worn by Monica Vitti in "Night", or the wool and fur coat that belonged to the Empress Farah Diba.
The models in the audience include Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria of Thurn and Taxi, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria and Sophie of Habsburg.
Naty Abascal and the designer in 2006
Many of these clients say that first Valentine's Day is like first love, "you can't forget it".
"I remember it perfectly.
They were pants, shirts, a gilet jacket and a jacket from the 1971-72 autumn-winter collection.
It was a gift he made me", says Naty Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to others for his femininity and his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty", adds the former Duchess of Feria.
"I really like the colors she uses, they brighten up a lot and give the face a "spark".
The proportions are perfect".
Even the princess and fashion icon Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg can't forget how she dressed for Valentine's Day for the first time.
When she was growing up and living in Italy, she longed to be of age and to have the opportunity to wear one of his evening dresses...
She finally made it to the late '90s.
"My first dress from Valentine's Day was for a celebration at the castle of my cousin, Prince Edward de Ligne.
