It was a dream come true", says the widow of Rodrigue d'Arenberg.
"Valentino is lax with fashion, his passion is timeless", explains the Italian aristocrat, whose life unfolds between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg has stored the designer's formal dress "very carefully... because the dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories that they have inside".
The "King" of Fashion
The highlight of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress from her wedding to Paul the Greek in 1995.
The ivory-colored silk dress, with twelve different types of cut, and a four-and-a-half-meter [4.5 m] length of pullover, took four months of work and 25 "beads" (as the designer of his sewing machine calls it) to make.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the foremost authority on the specialized press, these dresses represent a landmark of late 20th-century high fashion, "the return of high-society clientele".
Valentino, dazzled by the elitist "savoir-être" over the years, is now the best example of it.
Garavani as Cavaliere di Gran Croce (the highest honour in Italy), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres and awarded with the Order of the Legion of Honour accumulates as much honour as any of the husbands of his clients.
