He was flawless, time left no trace on him".
When the princess says so...
The hardest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the Kawah Ijen volcano area
For four euros, the volcanoes in Indonesia risk their lives and health to carry 70 pounds [70 kg] of sulfur down steep rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are people who literally work in hell.
That is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern island of Java in Indonesia.
That's why he has to work his way to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfur gases escape from the Earth's interior and become solid when exposed to the air.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, weighing up to 70 pounds [70 kg], he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along rough stone trails.
It is only a quarter mile [250 m] to the summit of the 2,386-meter-high volcano, but it takes over 40 minutes for the exhausted climbers to climb at a tortoise's pace, keeping their balance and carefully considering their steps so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners at Kawah Iwan make five cents for every pound of sulfur they mine
When they are up, they make their way past the tourists who photograph them like they're monkeys in a circus, and they tirelessly carry heavy baskets to a weight that the mining company has placed slightly lower, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining at the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
Then he sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since the mineral has a place in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because we normally carry 70 kilograms [70 lb], we earn about 46,000 rupees [$2,500] for each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes three hours and at the end of it he is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (US$11.50) a day.
Although this may seem a negligible amount for such inhuman efforts, it is three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wages of miners here are very high, for example, the coffee picking costs 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the fortnightly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", explains a porter who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as compelling as sulphur in Indonesia: "I married a young girl from Bali, who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and eyes irritated by toxic gases.
At 27 years old, Anto risks his life three times a day in Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him, even though he has a special mask and glasses to protect his face.
He's got asthma, he's got shortness of breath, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that are leaking out of the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'm going to work for two more years because I want to open a business or study Spanish or French", promises more than solid English.
This charming and intelligent young man, who could be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, is destined to become a porter.
She shares a dirty wooden shack with other porters and gets up at two o'clock every morning because the sulfur keeps boiling at night and her characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Despite the darkness, the pharaoh lighted Anto into the crater and illuminated his way with a small lantern, which he had attached to his helmet and bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers carry a basket of sulfur from the crater floor on their shoulders
Although the company has high revenues, it has not mechanised the extraction of sulphur for cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they don't even get a share of the 30,000 rupees ($2.5) photo surcharge, which, along with the 15,000 rupees ($1.2) ticket, is collected by the park rangers from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for livestock, not people", argues Madrusin, a 42-year-old heavy-duty porter who has been working in Kawah for only three decades since leaving school.
She can lift up to 300 pounds [110 kg], and she assures us that she will keep working "as long as she can", because she needs money to educate her three sons, ages 18 to 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here, because volcano was my whole life
Although the sulfur burns their throats and itch their eyes when the wind turns unexpectedly and catches the miners in the thick vapours coming out of the volcano, the miners are so adamant that none of them complain of serious illness... but this is evident from their frequent breathing difficulties, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder wounds caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only carry 50 kilograms at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which is then transported by three trucks down a steep path through the cluster to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano has been my whole life", Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, missing several teeth.
The oldest of his five sons, he is 30 years old, and he also earns his living by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the enduring misery of one of the world's most difficult crafts endures from generation to generation - crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for a baby to save the economy
Singaporeans are blaming not having children on careers, stress and the cost of living and education.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot, let's do our civic duty and breed a new life!
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a mint candy ad, but nevertheless - or perhaps that's why - a video went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These are the words of a rap that uses local "put the bucket in the oven" innuendo to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency that made the video, hopes that this ad will bring attention to the problem in a humorous way.
Douglas Hamilton, the agency's artistic director, says he wanted to use the influence of music to get people to do "their civic duty".
"It's purely an Internet thing, so it must have been fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in this country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing our population, so we felt that was a topic we had to touch on.
We knew the government was trying a lot of things like promoting pheromone perfumes or throwing a meet-and-greet.
Many of these ideas could be creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like compose rap, to solve this problem".
1.2 children
The one who doesn't take it lightly is the Singapore government.
They spend $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and allocates financial benefits.
All of these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative government and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore, in terms of population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered a recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Population Office, says that this is for "better education" and "broader career opportunities".
"People have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities, not just marriage and family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to postponing marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decline in Singapore's birth rate.
While there have been efforts within immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against population decline, this has caused dislike among local residents.
Some Singaporean websites show open xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for maintaining low wages and little effort to integrate.
Rising immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party last year recorded its worst election result since independence.
After the elections, there was an attempt to solve the problem by quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known implications for national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying to keep the housing stock down.
For example, it began to affect the real estate business.
The Urban Development Office has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments are 46 square meters and have been a great success in sales.
However, there are concerns that these apartments may encourage a youthful lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of EL Developers, claims that their "shoe boxes" sell far faster than larger homes.
"They are more popular, selling days to weeks faster than larger homes.
That's why they're so much better for our cash flow".
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited to offering too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed out
Singapore is a city state.
While these new rules could lead to an increase in the nation's birth rate, interviews with Singaporeans working in the city's financial district suggest they won't have much of an effect.
"People are always stressed, housing is expensive, and education is expensive, so many people put it off", says a young official.
"Let the rest have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time", says another young man in his early 20's.
Both men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons for not having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who ultimately have the final say on family formation.
