I don't know if anyone will answer me, I just put them in", he adds.
"Social networking is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or communicate quickly with friends", she says.
He says without hesitation that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask, and at the latter, he admits that he does not know 20 people on his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to this boy, none of them ever asked him for anything, nor did they ask for his address or phone number.
"If they insist or demand it, I simply remove them from my account", he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the Twitter recommendations.
These boys are no strangers to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who he was", he confirms.
According to Jose, the victim didn't log off the account.
"She just activated the private mode".
Then he explains a series of steps to set up an account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if I was bothered or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate student in Education, believes that for children and adolescents to navigate social networks properly, they need to understand that the main purpose of social networks is to inform them.
He states: "The Internet began as a means of finding information, but with the advent of social networks, the rules of the game have changed".
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of Yale University and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these terms to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people born in this age of technology.
We are digital immigrants, we have to teach them, and we are learning ourselves", she says.
He explains that this is a difficult subject "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature enough to do so".
Also, they should be prudent about their surroundings at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends, and not to think about the consequences", he adds.
According to this expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work", he adds.
Marrielos Porras goes on to list some possibilities: If there are things you would not tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, "Would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend's?"
You know what other people are saying about you?
When you tag people in photos of parties, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more thing: do they need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they have to behave in the online environment as well as the offline one.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, people are guided by respect, morality, and other principles, and the same should be true on social media", he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary school teacher, and educational consultant, explains that it is essential for parents to read the rules of social networking carefully.
"If they understand every little trick, they have a good basis for talking to their children about the consequences of opening an online account.
For example, about age or what is allowed to be shared or published", he says.
Guardia believes it's crucial to remind children of the traditional rule "don't talk to strangers".
The South American Summit is over and the Lima Declaration has not been released.
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today ended without the issuance of the Lima Declaration, which was ratified and supposedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the sixth meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but representatives of the Foreign Ministry and the President's Office, who initially stipulated that the document would be published after the summit, said that it would be published later on the website of the Peruvian government.
They further stated that the content was released by Peruvian President Ollanta Humal in several short press statements.
The press was restricted throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential meeting was transmitted in the press room without sound with the message "confidential meeting, no sound transmission".
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press spokesmen of some governments present at the talks, but not by the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of the presidents participating, which provoked the displeasure of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media, who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent out an email to the media with a "concluding statement" from the summit, but it is only a statement by President Humala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion, the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, despite the press's fervent demands.
The official ASPA website states that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities tried to ensure broadcasting for all journalists, but completely prevented the flow of information.
The Summit concluded with, inter alia, a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peruvian President Ollanta Humala and Chilean President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing the defence of both sides on Monday to hear the dispute initiated by Lima against Santiago.
"We will investigate and implement a judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are hearing today in this international court", President Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts", added Piñera, greeting President Humal with a handshake on the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, expressing its submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered the decision to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the Presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was instructed to open the morning speeches and conclude the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, informing that 16 agreements had been signed and 31 projects planned between South American countries, with an investment of 17 billion dollars.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are being extended".
He informed that actions are being supported to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organized crime, to improve access to medicines and cheap internet in all corners of South America and to joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters".
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not be victorious in nature, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future", added Humala.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport connectivity in different parts of South America, especially rural and border areas . . . so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties", the Peruvian president said in a speech read out loud.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and its transboundary axis from the coast to Brazil, and two others concern better connectivity with Ecuador, but did not elaborate.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return her to the Union of South American Nations", from which she is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is united and has good neighborly relations.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully discuss the International Court of Justice ruling on the maritime border dispute being contested by Bogotá.
"It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
"We will discuss all solutions, none are excluded, not even a treaty with Nicaragua that would require negotiations with this country", he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we should conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and precise way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City to attend the inauguration of President Enrique Peña Nieta.
The EU Ministers of Defence met at the Summit to approve provisionally the Action Plan for 2013, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
The members of UNASUR are Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru is the interim chairman of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn from Europe about integration
President Rafael Correa of Ecuador announced today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which "South America, in this case indeed, must learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state TV Perú that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are practically one nation".
In this sense, he defended the project of creating South American citizenship, which is supported by the member countries of Unasur.
"The free movement of citizens and workers within any South American country, which already exists between the members of the Andean Community, must be achieved, but there are still backward areas that want to return us to the past", he pointed out.
The Ecuadorian president expressed, among other things, his agreement to the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the condition that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states be reduced and that those who signed the San José Pact on Human Rights be taken into account.
"Those in charge never commit to anything, and we South Americans sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is funded in Washington by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he did not regret this decision, because it did not betray his principles and respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
He added that at the time, "there was reasonable suspicion that Assange could be extradited to a third country regardless of the ongoing trial".
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary for asking him to be interrogated on Swedish territory for an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish legislation itself allows for the interrogation to be carried out by videoconference call, which could be carried out from the Ecuadorian embassy in London".
Correa said there was a risk that Assange's physical and mental health would deteriorate.
"I haven't spoken to him since he's been at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a minor lung problem, but nothing serious", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
"But his physical and mental condition are in danger of deteriorating because he is confined to a small space with no possibility of movement in the fresh air.
This would affect everyone's health", he added.
President Correa noted that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian Embassy in London on the basis of a permit allowing him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the United Kingdom, Sweden and the European courts, and stressed that talks had been held with London to resolve the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
"We don't negotiate human rights, we don't use that word in this case, but there were constant conversations.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European courts, because Assange's lawyer Baltazar Garzón is leading a series of trials in various European bodies", he said.
He said that "if Britain issues a pass tomorrow, it's all over".
And if Sweden can interview Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as is easily possible under the law there and as has been done in other cases, tomorrow this problem will be put to an end".
Correa used the situation to present himself as a defender of press freedom, explaining that he does not tolerate "sub-average, bad intentions and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
The greatest enemies of the free press are not us, the mean and perverted politicians, but the bad journalists in the service of profit, coercion and blackmail", he said.
In this regard, he expressed his happiness that neither such journalists, "nor bankers, nor hegemonic countries, nor the bourgeoisie control Ecuador", and announced that if re-elected, "he will continue to change in the right way and in the right direction".
President Correa also supported the decision to keep the veto expressed by Paraguay on membership in the Unasur union at least until its next elections, arguing that the whole "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coup d'état wrapped in legality" because in fact "it has destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
The Ecuadorian president also said that he considered it "completely appropriate" that his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, negotiate with Nicaragua on the maritime boundary between the two countries now, in the wake of the International Court of Justice ruling in favor of Nicaragua.
The verdict is not being accepted at this time.
"This is a problem between a South American and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They need to be considered in a broad sense, so that they can be overcome and there is a way forward".
He also expressed hope for a settlement of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile, which is being heard by the same court, and expressed the view that "it is right for Latin America to seek international jurisdiction if both countries commit to accept a judgment, however harsh".
Regarding the possibility of running in the next presidential election in Ecuador, to run for a third term in office, he noted that he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes very difficult".
Correa has stated that if he loses the elections in February 2013, he will retire from public life.
"I have never been interested in power, but such injustices as socioeconomic poverty in Ecuador can only be remedied by political power.
My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so we must accept this responsibility", he said.
"If I win, it would be my last term as president, and then I would retire from politics.
If we lose, I'm going to do the same thing.
I've made my decision", he said.
Correa also mentioned the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez in Cuba.
"I just spoke to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolas Maduro, who says that President Chávez has gone for scheduled routine treatment and his return to Cuba was expected after the end of the campaign.
This is not a recurrence in the president's health", he explained.
The Ecuadorian head of state attended the sixth summit of heads of state and government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) today, which concluded with calls for greater regional integration in order to maintain development, equality and security.
AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizi was 21 when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was like being struck by lightning", he recalls, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "slightly soften", but apparently without success.
The boy kept it from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to inform about it, with such dedication that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the longest-serving patients in the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since he was 22, which was unthinkable in the early 1990s, when there was much doubt, few treatment options, and greater stigma.
At that time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him "because of the cut".
At the time, AIDS was a death sentence.
Now it's possible to survive this syndrome and live fully.
However, many people who do not know they have the disease only come to the hospital when the virus has destroyed their body and weakened their immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years after the world's first AIDS outbreak, or at least since the first documented cases, "it is a great achievement that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara, confirming this information in a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
Infectious disease and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the survival and longevity of a person depends on the degree of immune system damage in the patients diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not use drugs faring better: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can, according to this finding, "live without problems up to age 75, with treatment", the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth noting that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the death rate has declined significantly in recent years, and the number of AIDS deaths in Mexico has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the UNAIDS yearbook), it is also true that according to national statistics, 60 percent of AIDS patients have died since the discovery of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 as of May of this year.
Why do people keep dying from disease?
"I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it's done at my hospital.
We haven't used up our medicines for at least the last 12 years, and the problem is that patients come in at a very advanced stage, because they don't know the status of the disease, or the late stage of the disease".
He adds: "Nine out of ten patients come in with an associated infection, and the only thing we can do to make a bigger difference in overall mortality is to diagnose the disease early, so we need to offer screening tests on a large scale to all who ask".
His proposal is in line with the experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco, and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to a private laboratory for tests only because a friend did, and despite his young age, he already had an outbreak of AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather crap three times a week", they say, but that's not my case.
I've been eating healthy, exercising, taking medication".
To this day, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I do a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I take care of myself and the other person responsibly", says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO newspaper, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today, on World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they're at risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, that's better. And if they've been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like everyone else if they're responsible".
This message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a huge gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who investigates HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that are dedicated to this task, "the condom distribution has really increased, we used to get one or two, now we get packs and hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question, full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers, and health care workers, which teens want to avoid, says the reporter.
He proposed changing this inefficient distribution, that the condoms should not be just behind the counter, but that the 100 should be in the dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
"This is not a promotion of promiscuity.
It's not even about "paying for beer and a motel", as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if he would agree to condom distribution in his district.
It is best to make condoms available to those who already have sex", he noted.
Key figures in the state of Jalisco
13 435 cases have been reported (12 158 cases of AIDS and 1 317 cases of HIV).
This makes Mexico the fourth country in newly diagnosed AIDS cases and the 13th in HIV-related cases.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are blood-borne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people may be living with HIV, with four to five people for every recorded case who are unaware of the disease.
The judgment upheld by the United States Court of Appeal, which does not recognise the restructuring of Grupo Vitro's debt imposed by the bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an unfavourable precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the corporate restructuring procedures permitted by Mexican law do not seem to apply in the land of stripes and stars despite international agreements.
The approval of a ruling issued on June 15th of last year by Judge Harlin Hall in the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms practically defenseless against the possibility of confiscation of their assets across the river el Bravo.
Nevertheless, the ruling opens the door for a major Mexican glass manufacturer to appeal to the United States Supreme Court against three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge in this case maintains that creditors are to follow United States bankruptcy law, the New Orleans-based Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, this would indicate a lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of multinational enterprises.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law on the Unification of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, which designates the American Law Institute as the arbitrator.
Second, the judgment states that without a vote by the branches from the internal structure of the company, when the debts of the parent company Vitro vis-à-vis the branches are recognised, the majority required to approve the restructuring would not be reached.
However, this option is allowed by Mexican law.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first to adopt this scheme.
There are half a dozen examples, like Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose domestic debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
Moreover, it is true that even after the votes of the branches had been counted, the creditors - who had brought a case against Vitro in the United States, i.e. the 'soup' funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have reached a majority.
They'd get about 45 percent to 37 in the vote.
The Court of Appeal disregards that fact.
In the alternative, the Court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the background of the severe economic crisis that hit the United States.
In the meantime, the family firm of González Sady will appeal the re-evaluation directly to the Court of Appeal, so that the re-evaluation takes place in full attendance, that is, with the participation of five judges, since originally only three voted.
If he fails here, he will seek re-examination of the case by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
The Court's failure to refer to the document sent by the Mexican Government as an amicus curiae service, which details Vitro's proceedings under the Bankruptcy Act, and which points out that the company has taken the liberty of agreeing to agreements signed by both countries to confront the Act with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act, is significant in the present case.
Moreover, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations International Trade Commission, i.e. the rules designed for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
A collision on both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
The overall assessment
For months, a criminal complaint by the Mexican aviation unions against the former owner of Gaston Azcárraga Andrade, who was accused of fraudulent dealings, had been lying on the table without being noticed, and according to the pilots' union, the vessels had already leaked.
The court headed by Carlos Díaz Chávez Morineau has just filed a lawsuit against the National Banking Commission and the Securities and Exchange Commission, accusing them of obstruction of justice.
According to the Commission, the Authority systematically refused to report to the Prosecutor General's Office the transaction carried out by this entrepreneur, in which he withdrew 198 million pesos from the IXE bank from the F/589 trust fund on behalf of Mexican Airlines.
The funds were most likely directed towards the purchase of shares of the Professional Hotel Administration (Administradora Profesional de Hoteles).
As is known, Azcarraga Andrade is the majority shareholder of the Posadas hotel chain.
The Siege of Dragon Mart
A group of local and foreign environmentalists, academics, businessmen and ordinary citizens gathered at the Universidad de Caribe campus over the weekend to approve the formation of an association to prevent the opening of the Chinese Dragon Mart in Cancun.
We are talking, as you know, about a huge commercial and distribution center with products from the "land of the big wall" focused on Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean, which would include a residential area at the bottom for employees of 150 companies.
The Canacintra (Cámara Nacional de la Industria de Transformación) has already managed to unite the governors of the south-eastern zone to oppose a monumental site that would partly devastate the protected areas and which is the source of all resistance to industry.
The end of the ACTA affair
The request of the Senate, which the government ignored and which requested an explanation of the conditions and circumstances under which the Mexican Ambassador to Japan signed the Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement, known by its English acronym ACTA, according to the Mexican Institute of Industrial Property (Instituto Mexicano de la Propiedad Industrial), has become obsolete.
As is known, this happened despite the fact that the Senate itself ruled out considering it a threat to free expression on social networks.
Homex in the long term
In an effort to pay off long-term debts and not affect short-term ones, Homex developers are putting 500 million pesos of investment certificates on the market.
This series is the first of four identical ones that offer interest payments every 28 days.
Competitive is born
The merger of leading IT companies such as NYCE, e-Quálity and Kernet has created an association with the trade name Competival, which will target the software services market in Central and South America.
