Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
World champion basketball player Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been involved with the sport for over 60 years, traveling the world with it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of local basketball history as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before a stroke in 2008 confined him to a wheelchair, Reyes had been passionate about the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, a player in the National Basketball League (BSN), the owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón team in the National Basketball League, or the president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
"I have been in many roles in my life in basketball, including several at the same time, such as being president of the BSN National League, general manager of the national team and president of the federation in the 1990s", Reyes recalled during a visit to reporters from Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia from his long career, bear this out.
Bayamon in the heart
With the greatest of all movements, the guards are those who recall his time at Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or team owner.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to compete with the team los Vaqueros since 1967, eight championships, whether as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship -- 1981 when Jerome Mincy made his BSN debut.
"The team then took over from 'Cuco' Ortiz, who was an excellent leader", Reyes said.
"I remember Gene Bartow, who was the former coach here at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, and he said, 'I've got a six-foot-tall player for you.
You want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended me to quarterback Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brings Bayamon a championship win, Gausse will then contribute to the next one".
Gausse enjoyed the championship for the Los Vaqueros, but only from a distance, as he was already president of the basketball federation in 1988.
At the time, he wanted to focus on his duties and enjoy Mincy's place on the national team.
"I remember the first time we beat the United States in an Olympic qualifier in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, but we should have had bronze if it wasn't for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final throw", Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
He's one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the United States team, which was pretty much the same team that beat us to bronze at the World Championships.
This squad not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fica López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also included youngsters (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be on the team in 1990 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have had the perfect lineup, but managed to win the gold medal and bring us great joy, was the team from the 1995 Olympic qualifiers in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players on the roster like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner, who replaced players disqualified from the Mar de Plata Pan American Games, we won gold against all odds.
What was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His numbers in international tournaments are impressive.
No Puerto Rican has achieved the level of success that Piculin has.
Not to mention his involvement in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very difficult.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I'm very fond of Leo Arill's work.
What do you consider your greatest accomplishment in the Federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, and that in the early '90s, the National League had 17 teams in one season.
What did you fail to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
For example, Ponce boys would only play in their area and compete with teams from other parts of the island only in the national play-offs.
Now kids travel a lot and play too many games, which is not necessary.
I also see the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
I'm glad to hear that.
What are you doing now?
I listen to music mostly, watch YouTube music videos from my time, enjoy my grandchildren, and sometimes go to basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been there for me.
The actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". on the television series Dallas, in which he portrayed a man who acted recklessly and was cunning and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the rapacious oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series Dallas became a symbol of hunger in the '80s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in the new Dallas series this year, died, according to an official family announcement provided to the Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros., on Friday afternoon from complications related to cancer.
